{"version":2,"ops":[{"type":1,"author":{"id":"4f00b071b1954af5dec4d463e8167798000a9677"},"timestamp":1770401185,"metadata":{"github-id":"I_kwDORKQ0ks7o7XWD","github-url":"https://github.com/myyoda/principles-paper/issues/7","origin":"github"},"title":"Rename to VAMP","message":"Good acronyms typically have these hallmarks (as summarized by Claude and seconded by me):\n\n**Memorable** - Easy to recall and recognize\n**Pronounceable** - Can be spoken as a word (NASA, RADAR)\n**Meaningful** - The acronym itself suggests or relates to its purpose\n**Clear Components** - Each letter represents an important, distinct concept\n**Logical Order** - The sequence of words flows naturally\n**Widely Applicable** - The concepts are fundamental and broadly relevant\n**Action-Oriented** - Often describes principles or goals\n**Balanced** - Each component carries similar weight/importance\n**Self-Explanatory** - The expanded form clarifies the concept\n**Not Forced** - Doesn't sacrifice clarity for the sake of making a word\n\nA great example is FAIR.\n\nHere is a table summarizing the pro's and con's between YODA and VAMP (again, started in Claude and polished by me)\n\n| Aspect | YODA (Yoda's Organogram for Data Analysis) | VAMP (Versioned, Actionable, Modular, Portable) |\n|--------|----------------------------------------|--------------------------------------------------|\n| **Memorability** | ✅ Strong - pop culture reference\u003cbr\u003e⚠️ Potential Legal Issues - Used only as a word or title only, this is less of an issue (see [JEDI](https://jedi.readthedocs.io/en/latest/))\u003cbr\u003e❌Potential Legal Issues - But any use of logos puts us in a legal grey area regarding derivative trademarks (e.g., GIFs, [read more](https://www.wired.com/story/baby-yoda-gif-copyright/)) which can result in complications, including but not limited to personal financial liability | ✅ Strong - injectable into the common phrase \"re-VAMP pipelines\"|\n| **Pronunciation** | ✅ Easy and natural | ✅ Easy and natural |\n| **Meaning Alignment** | ❌ Weak - relies on Star Wars, which has no inherent connection to data analysis | ✅ Strong - suggests speed, modernization, enhancement |\n| **Component Clarity** | ❌ Poor - \"Yoda's Organogram\" is confusing and forced | ✅ Excellent - each term is clear and technical |\n| **Logical Order** | ⚠️ Neutral - order seems arbitrary | ✅ Good - follows pipeline development lifecycle |\n| **Domain Relevance** | ❌ Weak - \"Organogram\" is about org charts, not data | ✅ Strong - all terms are standard in data engineering |\n| **Action-Oriented** | ⚠️ Mixed - \"Analysis\" is clear, rest is vague | ✅ Strong - \"Actionable\" explicitly action-oriented |\n| **Professional Tone** | ❌ Poor - too playful for scientific/technical context | ✅ Excellent - professional and technical |\n| **Self-Explanatory** | ❌ No - requires explanation of why \"Yoda's Organogram\" | ✅ Yes - each component describes a best practice |\n| **Forced/Contrived** | ❌ Very forced - awkward backronym | ✅ Natural - terms genuinely describe pipeline principles |\n| **Pipeline Specificity** | ❌ Low - generic \"analysis\" | ✅ High - directly addresses pipeline architecture |\n| **Adoption Potential** | ❌ Low - difficult to take seriously | ✅ High - sounds authoritative and practical |\n\nFWIW, here is what Claude said about this table\n\n\u003e VAMP is significantly stronger as an acronym for pipeline principles. It's professional, meaningful, and each component directly addresses critical aspects of robust data processing pipelines.\n\nwhen given the neutral prompt\n\n\u003e Make a markdown table for summarizing the pros and cons of using YODA (Yoda's Organogram Data Analysis) vs. VAMP (Versioned, Actionable, Modular, Portable) as an acronym for guiding principles for constructing reproducible data processing or analysis pipelines\n\nCredit: from @asmacdo's memory, it was Adina who came up with VAMP originally - though only proof he was able to find of earliest mention was a talk by Michael (https://files.inm7.de/mih/pres/talks/whatisdatalad_2023.html#/2/3). If the change is accepted by the group we should try to pin down the original attribution for more accurate due credit\n\nTeam VAMP: @asmacdo, Adina/Michael(?), @CodyCBakerPhD, Claude\n\nTeam YODA: @yarikoptic","files":null}]}